            <script>
              document.getElementById('patternsModal5-content2').innerHTML =
                marked('Most Telcos have traditionally distinguished their products based on when customers were charged for consumption. Customers who have low consumption requirements or have poor or non-existent credit-ratings are typically offered pre-paid products with relatively simple pricing structures. Customers purchase credit in advance for these pre-paid products, and they are charged immediately after the completion of consumption. Customers with pre-paid products tend to be cautious about their spending, as they are able to correlate their consumption directly with charging. Post-paid products were initially targeted at individuals with good credit-rating who were not as conscientious about their spend as the average pre-paid customer, closely mimicking the business model offered by credit card companies. With the increased gap between consumption and charging, customers are likely to increase the volume of their consumption. In the absence of little or no initial regulation, customers were increasingly faced with high bills. In order to allay fears of further high bills, a variety of cost-saving measures were made available to post-paid customers. The most common cost-saving measure was to pre-purchase a certain amount of calling, messaging, and data volume in advance, typically on a recurring basis in the form of a subscription. Given the variety calling, messaging, data consumption habits, it did not take long for a high variety of subscriptions to emerge. By further linking these post-paid subscriptions to subsidized devices, where customers would receive free or discounted devices in exchange for termed commitments, customers were faced with even greater choice for post-paid products. Thus while pre-paid products remained structurally simple and processable within moments after consumption, post-paid products grew increasingly complex and required more complex processing. Mimicking the customer’s deferred payment, post-paid consumption began to be processed in closer synchronization the  customer’s payment cycle. Separate systems were used for pre-paid and post-paid charging. The relatively simple processing structures of post-paid products allowed them to be processed by a standard network component called the Intelligent Network, while post-paid products were processed by specialized billing systems. Most Telcos had the tendency to develop their own customized billing systems to process their post-paid products in the 1980s to early 2000, given their market differentiated post-paid portfolio and the lack of mature commmercial-off-the-shelf billing systems. Distinctions were required between rating, which evaluated the individual event of consumption, with periodic charging, where all individually rated events are considered collectively, although such clear distinctions between rating and charging is inconsistently applied. Replacing these highly customized billing systems with commercial off-the-shelf systems are usually complex undertakings, especially given that the high variety of post-paid products are usually migrated to these new implementations. While technology systems are firmly divided into pre-paid and post-paid worlds, the consumption habits of customers have changed. Pre-paid produts have lost their social stigma of being associated with poor credit-ratings, and customers with strong credit-ratings purchase over-the-top products such as Voice over IP (VOIP), Music, and Movies in pre-paid configurations from providers other than the Telco. Conversely, it is increasingly common for customers to have a post-paid product for connectivity and have pre-paid over-the-top products (e.g. consume applications or music on demand) or have pre-paid products for connectivity and have subscriptions for content (e.g. monthly music or movie subscriptions). These over-the-top products operate in a competitive marketplace, and the market leaders provide customers with consumption and charging history as it occurs. Customers are increasingly having to cope with fragmented charging for the consumption, where some of the charging information is provided by the Telco, some by marketplace where the product was purchased, and some within the charging features of the product itself. While most customers would probably prefer consolidated charging and reporting from a single party, it is yet to emerge whether that party will be the Telco, the Device Manufacturer, the Device’s Operating System provider, or a Product that operates on the Device’s Operating System. The winner will probably be the party that generates the greatest trust through transparency and reliability in charging.');
