                marked('<hr />*Marketing 300 free minutes of call time rather than 5 hours can lead customers to prime themselves to believe that the net sum of their individual conversations are shorter than they actually are. See Bargh, J. A., & Chartrand, T. L. 1999. The unbearable automaticity of being. American Psychologist 54(7), 462–479.\n[Walker, W.R. and Snowronski, J.J. 2003. Life Is Pleasant—and Memory Helps to Keep It That Way! Review of General Psychology Copyright. Vol. 7, No. 2, 203–210.](//www.apa.org/pubs/journals/releases/gpr-72203.pdf)<br /><br />Most individuals tend to believe that they are in greater control of their behaviour than they actually are, and that they exhibit this controlled behaviour with consistency. See Langer, E. J. 1975. The illusion of control. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology 32(2), 311–328. Goethals, G. R., & Reckman, R. F. 1973. The perception of consistency in attitudes. Journal of Experimental Social Psychology 9(6), 491–501. For a more accessible explanation, see ["How the Consistency Bias Warps Our Personal and Political Memories"](//www.spring.org.uk/2008/02/how-consistency-bias-warps-our-personal.php)*');
