            <script>
              document.getElementById('patternsModal5-content4').innerHTML =
                marked('Therefore rate and charge customers immediately after consumption, irrespective of when customers choose to pay for that consumption. Each individual charge is then entered as a debit record for the customer’s balance. Customers can make payments at any time, and their payments are entered as credits for their balance. The time interval and minimum payable amounts that customers must credit are a function of an individual customer’s loyalty and history of past payments which establishes their creditworthiness. A customer with poor creditworthiness must credit their account before being able to use any services that will debit that account. A customer with better creditworthiness use services that debit their account without having credited it beforehand with pre-defined limits. A customer with excellent creditworthiness will be able use services to much higher pre-defined limits. Make it clear to customers that their creditworthiness is a function of their timely payments and loyalty, and reward their timely payments and loyalty with a better creditworthiness. Provide customers with the option to move the charging of their over-the-top products and services, which they settle through other payment channels, to a consolidated payment channel managed by the Telco. The financial liquidity of a customer is subject to change, and in difficult moments of their lives, provide customers that have been loyal some leeway in making their payments. Provide advisory services for customers in financial difficulty on how they can optimize their consumption to lower their overall charges, such as removing or reducing the consumption of certain non-essential products. Permit customers to reduce their payable amounts with aggregated loyalty points at all times. Make the entire charging platform accessible to third-parties so that they can easily provide products and services through the Telco. Make it possible for customers to understand their consumption based on a variety of views, such as their timeline, location, format, or provider of their consumption. Give customers the option to use a variety of payment methods, such as direct debits from their bank accounts or paying cash at a store of the Telco. If possible, avoid payment channels that create debt for customers or act as a payment consolidator, such as credit cards. In affect, Telcos can assume the role of credit cards with greater flexibility and trust.');
            </script>
